    "quote": "A small set of well-understood principles can explain a sky full of motion.",
    "bio": "Aryabhata was born in 476 CE and became one of classical India’s most influential mathematical astronomers. At about twenty-three, he composed the Aryabhatiya, a compact work written in verse so that complex methods could be memorised and transmitted. In it, he gave algorithms for arithmetic, algebra, trigonometry and astronomical calculation. His approximation of π was remarkably accurate for its time, and his sine table helped turn geometry into a practical computational tool. He also explained that the apparent daily motion of the stars results from Earth rotating on its axis, and he treated eclipses as shadows rather than supernatural events.\n\nAryabhata worked without telescopes, electronic calculators or modern notation. His challenge was to transform repeated observations of the sky into numerical rules using only geometry, logic and hand calculation. Because scientific ideas were recorded in compressed Sanskrit verses, later scholars had to interpret, test and extend his methods. Some of his conclusions were debated, yet his willingness to replace myth with measurement helped establish a durable Indian tradition of mathematical astronomy.\n\nHis journey shows that scientific power does not begin with sophisticated equipment. It begins with careful observation, abstraction and the courage to describe nature quantitatively. The same trigonometric ratios, approximations and equations studied in Classes XI and XII are descendants of the intellectual tools Aryabhata used to understand planetary motion and time.",
    "inspireWhy": "Aryabhata should inspire PCM students to treat mathematics as a language for explaining the physical world. He proves that disciplined calculation, clear assumptions and curiosity can produce ideas that remain useful for centuries.",
