    "tag": "MATHEMATICIAN · ASTRONOMER",
    "quote": "Do not fear an abstract idea; define it carefully and it may change the world.",
    "bio": "Brahmagupta, born around 598 CE, led an astronomical school at Bhillamala and wrote the Brahmasphutasiddhanta in 628. His most transformative contribution was to give systematic arithmetic rules involving zero and negative numbers. He described a number minus itself as zero, explained operations with debts and fortunes, and treated zero as a number within calculation. Although one of his rules involving division by zero was not correct by modern standards, his framework was a decisive step towards the number system students now use automatically.\n\nHe also developed methods for solving quadratic equations, worked with indeterminate equations, created interpolation techniques and gave the celebrated formula for the area of a cyclic quadrilateral. In astronomy, he calculated planetary positions, eclipses and conjunctions. His work travelled through translations and helped carry Indian numerals and mathematical methods into the Islamic world and, eventually, Europe.\n\nBrahmagupta’s life reminds us that progress often includes partial answers. He did not inherit today’s algebraic symbols, coordinate system or calculators; he had to express algorithms in verse and defend ideas that challenged ordinary intuition. Zero is especially difficult: it represents absence, yet it must participate consistently in calculation. By giving this “nothing” a mathematical role, he made more advanced algebra, commerce, science and computing possible. His intellectual courage lay not in avoiding mistakes, but in constructing rules clear enough for later mathematicians to test and improve.",
    "inspireWhy": "Students should learn from Brahmagupta that mathematics grows by defining ideas precisely. A difficult concept becomes powerful when its rules are stated, tested and refined—even when the first version is not perfect.",
