    "tag": "MATHEMATICIAN · ASTRONOMER",
    "quote": "Learn the method deeply enough to improve it, explain it and pass it on.",
    "bio": "Bhaskara II, also called Bhaskaracharya, was born in 1114 and became head of the astronomical observatory at Ujjain. His Siddhanta Shiromani was organised into four major parts: Lilavati on arithmetic, Bijaganita on algebra, Grahaganita on planetary mathematics and Goladhyaya on spheres. Through memorable problems involving merchants, flowers, shadows, journeys and unknown quantities, he made mathematical reasoning practical and engaging.\n\nBhaskara developed sophisticated methods for equations, surds and indeterminate problems. His chakravala, or cyclic method, was an exceptionally effective algorithm for equations later associated with Pell. In astronomy he calculated planetary motion, eclipses and time. His writing also contains early ideas related to instantaneous motion and maxima and minima—concepts that resemble parts of differential calculus, although they were not expressed in the later formal language of limits and derivatives.\n\nHis achievement came in a world without printed textbooks or standard symbolic notation. Mathematical knowledge could be lost if teaching lineages broke, so he wrote in a form designed to be remembered and explained. He also built on Aryabhata and Brahmagupta instead of treating discovery as an isolated act. That continuity is part of his greatness: he mastered earlier work, corrected it, extended it and made it teachable. Bhaskara’s life demonstrates that elegant presentation and deep reasoning are not opposites. A beautiful problem can train exact thought, and a well-designed algorithm can outlive the person who created it.",
