    "quote": "Practise on models, learn from evidence and earn the right to handle real responsibility.",
    "bio": "Sushruta is remembered through the Sushruta Samhita, a foundational Sanskrit medical text compiled and expanded over centuries. Tradition places him in ancient India, though historians debate his exact date. The text describes anatomy, fractures, wound care, surgical instruments, cataract procedures and reconstructive operations, including methods related to rhinoplasty. It also stresses cleanliness, observation, patient examination and systematic training.\n\nWhat makes the account especially inspiring is its practical approach to learning. Students were advised to practise incisions and suturing on vegetables, leather bags, reeds and animal tissues before treating people. This resembles modern simulation-based education: build hand skill, understand material behaviour and reduce risk before performing a real procedure. The text catalogued numerous instruments and linked their shapes to specific functions, showing an early engineering mindset as well as medical knowledge.\n\nAncient surgery faced enormous limits. There were no antibiotics, modern anaesthesia, imaging systems or germ theory. Outcomes depended on anatomical understanding, careful preparation and disciplined technique. The surviving work also reflects the collective knowledge of generations rather than a single untouched manuscript, reminding us that science is preserved by communities that copy, question and improve it. Sushruta’s legacy is therefore not merely a list of operations; it is a model of evidence-based craft. He treated the body as something that could be studied through observation and trained practice rather than explained only through speculation.",
    "inspireWhy": "For PCM students, Sushruta shows how physics, chemistry and mathematics meet in real life: forces act on bones, materials determine instruments, solutions clean wounds and measurement guides safe procedures. Science becomes meaningful when knowledge is converted into skill and service.",
