    "name": "Jagadish Chandra Bose",
    "tag": "PHYSICIST · BIOPHYSICIST · INVENTOR",
    "quote": "When the laboratory you need does not exist, begin by creating it.",
    "bio": "Jagadish Chandra Bose was born in 1858 in Bengal and trained in physics at Cambridge and London. At Presidency College in Calcutta, he faced racial discrimination: Indian professors were paid less than Europeans and laboratory support was poor. Bose refused to accept unequal salary for several years, continued teaching and eventually received equal treatment with arrears. Rather than allowing limited resources to end his research, he designed and built much of his own apparatus.\n\nIn the 1890s he produced and detected millimetre-scale microwaves, demonstrating reflection, refraction, polarisation and other optical-like behaviour at radio frequencies. He devised sensitive detectors and publicly demonstrated wireless signalling before radio became a major industry. Later he crossed disciplinary boundaries and studied electrical responses in plants and materials. His crescograph magnified tiny plant movements, helping him investigate how living tissues respond to light, heat, chemicals and injury.\n\nBose’s career was unusual because he refused to divide nature into rigid academic compartments. He moved from electromagnetic waves to semiconductor-like detectors and then to plant physiology, always guided by instruments and measurable signals. He was also hesitant to patent discoveries, believing knowledge should serve humanity, though this choice meant others sometimes gained greater commercial recognition. In 1917 he founded the Bose Institute as a centre for interdisciplinary research. His life demonstrates scientific independence: when equipment, status and funding were inadequate, he responded by inventing better experiments and institutions.",
    "inspireWhy": "Bose should inspire students to build, test and measure—not merely memorise. He shows that school concepts such as waves, resonance and electrical response can become instruments that open entirely new fields of inquiry.",
