    "name": "Prafulla Chandra Ray",
    "tag": "CHEMIST · INDUSTRIAL PIONEER",
    "quote": "Knowledge becomes transformative when it is converted into products, institutions and opportunity for others.",
    "bio": "Prafulla Chandra Ray was born in 1861 in Bengal and developed a love of science despite prolonged illness interrupting his early schooling. After studying chemistry at Edinburgh, he returned to India and joined Presidency College, where colonial discrimination limited the positions and resources available to Indian scholars. He nevertheless built a productive research group and became known for work on nitrites and related inorganic compounds, including the preparation and study of mercurous nitrite.\n\nRay believed science should strengthen society, not remain confined to academic papers. In 1892 he began making chemicals with modest resources; this effort grew into Bengal Chemical and Pharmaceutical Works, one of India’s earliest major chemical enterprises. He wanted the country to develop scientific manufacturing rather than depend entirely on imported medicines and laboratory materials. He also wrote A History of Hindu Chemistry, connecting modern research with India’s earlier scientific traditions.\n\nHis personal life was marked by simplicity. Much of his income supported students, relief work and education. He mentored younger chemists and treated the creation of a scientific community as important as his own discoveries. Starting an indigenous chemical industry under colonial economic conditions was difficult: capital was scarce, technical infrastructure weak and imported products dominant. Ray persisted because he saw laboratory chemistry, entrepreneurship and national self-reliance as parts of the same mission. His career is a reminder that a scientist can be an investigator, teacher, institution-builder and ethical citizen at once.",
    "inspireWhy": "Class XI–XII students should learn from Ray that equations and reactions acquire power when they solve practical problems. A chapter on inorganic chemistry may be the starting point for a medicine, a manufacturing process or a national capability.",
