    "name": "C. V. Raman",
    "tag": "PHYSICIST · NOBEL LAUREATE",
    "quote": "A familiar colour can hide a new law of nature if you look at it with a scientist’s attention.",
    "bio": "Chandrasekhara Venkata Raman was born in 1888 and showed exceptional academic ability from an early age. Because a full-time scientific career in colonial India offered few secure opportunities, he initially joined the Indian Finance Service. Yet he continued experimental research before and after office hours at the Indian Association for the Cultivation of Science in Calcutta. His path proves that a delayed opportunity need not mean an abandoned calling.\n\nRaman was fascinated by light, colour, sound and the physical explanation of ordinary experiences. During a sea voyage, he questioned why the Mediterranean looked intensely blue and pursued the scattering of light in liquids. In 1928, Raman and his collaborators observed that a small fraction of light emerging from a substance has a changed frequency. The shift reveals molecular vibrational and rotational energies. This Raman effect became the basis of Raman spectroscopy, now used to identify chemicals, examine materials, detect medicines and study biological samples without destroying them.\n\nThe experiments were performed with comparatively simple apparatus: sunlight or a mercury lamp, filters, a spectrograph and exceptional care. Raman demonstrated that world-class discovery did not require waiting for a perfectly equipped foreign laboratory. In 1930 he became the first Asian Nobel laureate in a scientific field. He later built institutions, trained researchers and continued working with intense curiosity. His life also included disagreements and institutional struggles, but he remained committed to independent experimentation and to developing science in India.",
    "inspireWhy": "Raman should inspire students to ask scientific questions about everyday sights and sounds. The difference between noticing and discovering is disciplined measurement, repeated testing and the willingness to follow a question farther than others do.",
