    "name": "Meghnad Saha",
    "tag": "ASTROPHYSICIST · SCIENCE BUILDER",
    "quote": "Your starting point may limit comfort, but it does not have to limit the scale of your question.",
    "bio": "Meghnad Saha was born in 1893 to a poor shopkeeper’s family in a village near Dhaka. Continuing education required scholarships, long travel and extraordinary determination. As a student he faced social prejudice and was expelled from one school for participating in the Swadeshi movement. These obstacles did not reduce his ambition; they sharpened his belief that education and scientific institutions could transform society.\n\nSaha’s greatest contribution was the thermal ionisation equation developed around 1920. By combining thermodynamics, statistical ideas and atomic physics, the equation links temperature and pressure to the proportion of atoms in different ionisation states. Astronomers could now interpret stellar spectra: the strength of spectral lines did not simply mean one star contained more of an element, but could reflect how temperature changes the element’s ionisation. His theory helped turn spectroscopy into a quantitative method for determining the physical conditions inside stars.\n\nSaha also worked to build national scientific capacity. He supported research institutions, scientific journals, river planning, calendar reform and the public use of science. Later he entered Parliament, believing technical knowledge should inform national policy. His life was not a smooth march through privileged laboratories. It was a journey from economic hardship to international astrophysics, followed by a deliberate return to public problems. He demonstrated that equations can connect the microscopic behaviour of electrons with the light of distant stars—and that scientists can connect scholarship with nation-building.",
    "inspireWhy": "Saha should inspire students who feel limited by background or resources. Mastery of thermodynamics, spectra and algebra allowed him to read the temperature of stars. Strong fundamentals can carry a learner far beyond the circumstances in which learning begins.",
